par(mfrow = c(2,2))

# plot housebolds ~ total rooms

housing_prices %>% 
  ggplot(aes(total_rooms, households)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)


# households ~ population

housing_prices %>% 
  ggplot(aes(population, households)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)


# population ~ total_rooms 

housing_prices %>% 
  ggplot(aes(total_rooms, population)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)


# median_house_value ~ median_income

housing_prices %>% 
  ggplot(aes(median_income, median_house_value)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)

task 5 ##########

# regress median_house_value ~ median_income

lm1 <- lm(median_house_value ~ median_income, data = housing_prices)

summary(lm1)

Call:
lm(formula = median_house_value ~ median_income, data = housing_prices)

Residuals:
    Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
-513966  -51564  -13979   36549  403935 

Coefficients:
              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
(Intercept)    45457.0     1359.0   33.45   <2e-16 ***
median_income  39987.0      339.9  117.64   <2e-16 ***
---
Signif. codes:  0 *** 0.001 ** 0.01 * 0.05 . 0.1   1

Residual standard error: 74870 on 19673 degrees of freedom
Multiple R-squared:  0.4129,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.4129 
F-statistic: 1.384e+04 on 1 and 19673 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(lm1)

  • residuals vs fitted - flat line indicates that there is a good random scattering therefore residuals are independent
  • normal q-q - line shows a fairly straight line indicating a normal distribution
  • scale-location - residuals appear fairly randomly spread which satisfies the assumption of homoskedasticity
  • residuals vs leverage - cant see any cooks distance lines therefore the outlier cases are not influential

diagnostics fairly similar to before, better fit for assumption of homoskedasticity

lm2


Call:
lm(formula = median_house_value ~ median_income + housing_median_age, 
    data = housing_prices)

Coefficients:
       (Intercept)       median_income  housing_median_age  
             -7998               42420                1568

results suggest a 1 unit increase in median_income is associated with a 42420 increase in median_house_value on average

a 1 unit increase in housing_median_age is associated with a 1568 increase in median_house_age on average

task 1 ##########

lm3


Call:
lm(formula = median_house_value ~ log(median_income) + housing_median_age + 
    population + log(median_income):housing_median_age, data = housing_prices)

Coefficients:
                          (Intercept)                     log(median_income)                     housing_median_age  
                           -12674.297                             130280.757                                989.159  
                           population  log(median_income):housing_median_age  
                                2.988                                455.932

I would say the predicator is justified given that it would be expected that given a persons age, they are more likely to have a higher income having a greater impact on the median housing price.

should probably change median_house_value to natural logarithm to counter a non-linear distribution for a more accurate model.
